# Finance Tracker — Project Rules

## What this project is

A **private, local-only** Python tool that imports bank/credit card CSV
exports, categorises transactions, stores them in SQLite, and generates
spending reports. Stdlib only — no external dependencies, no network
calls, ever. This is a deliberate privacy constraint, not an oversight.

## Hard constraints — never violate these

- **No network calls of any kind.** No `requests`, no `urllib` for
  external hosts, no telemetry, no "phone home" anything. This tool's
  entire value proposition is that financial data never leaves the
  user's machine.
- **No external pip dependencies.** Everything must run with stdlib only
  (`csv`, `sqlite3`, `pathlib`, `datetime`, `hashlib`, `argparse`,
  `collections`). If a task seems to need a package, find a stdlib way
  first and ask before adding a dependency.
- **Never commit real financial data.** `data/accounts/*.csv`,
  `data/credit_card/*.csv`, and `db/*.db` must stay gitignored. Only
  `.gitkeep` placeholders belong in those folders in version control.
- **Fail loudly, never silently corrupt.** When parsing untrusted CSV
  input (dates, amounts), prefer raising an exception that gets caught
  and reported per-row over guessing or coercing a value that might be
  wrong. A skipped row with a clear error is always better than a wrong
  number silently entering someone's financial totals. (This is why
  `parse_amount` has a £100,000 sanity ceiling — see git history /
  CURSOR_PROMPT.md for the bug this fixed.)

## Architecture

- `db_layer.py` — SQLite schema + insert/update functions. Every
  transaction is fingerprinted (`make_hash`) from
  `date|description|amount|source_account` so re-importing the same file
  never creates duplicates. Don't change the hash formula without
  considering that it will treat all previously-imported data as "new"
  on next run (effectively re-importing everything). Manual category
  overrides live in `category_overrides` (keyed by normalized
  description) and are applied via `resolve_category()`.
- `importer.py` — CSV → DB. Two formats: bank (`Transaction Date,
  Transaction Type, Sort Code, Account Number, Transaction Description,
  Debit Amount, Credit Amount, Balance`, tab or comma delimited, debit/
  credit are separate columns) and credit card (`Date, Description,
  Amount`, sign auto-detected per file). Auto-detects delimiter via
  `csv.Sniffer`. Spending is always stored as a **negative** amount,
  income/credit as positive, regardless of source format. Uses
  `resolve_category()` so manual overrides win over keyword rules.
- `categoriser.py` — thin wrapper that applies `rules/categories.py`
  keyword matching to a description string. First matching category
  wins; order in the rules dict matters.
- `recategorise.py` — re-applies keyword rules to all DB rows via
  `resolve_category()` (manual overrides preserved).
- `rules/categories.py` — the only file end users should need to edit
  regularly. Keyword lists per category, plus `NON_SPENDING_CATEGORIES`
  (excluded from spend totals — transfers, card repayments, income) and
  `NEEDS_CATEGORIES` / `WANTS_CATEGORIES` (for the 50/30/20 benchmark).
- `report_data.py` — pure data functions for reports (dicts/lists, no
  print/HTTP). Shared by `analyze.py` and `web_server.py`.
- `analyze.py` — thin CLI wrapper over `report_data`; formats output via
  `print_*` functions. CSV export via `--export`.
- `web_server.py` — stdlib HTTP server on **127.0.0.1 only**; serves
  `web/static/` and JSON `/api/*` endpoints from `report_data`. Read-only
  for imports; supports local category edits via `POST
  /api/transaction/category` (updates all rows with the same normalized
  description and persists an override).

## Conventions

- All currency values are `float` GBP, negative = money out.
- Dates are stored as ISO `YYYY-MM-DD` strings in the DB regardless of
  source format.
- `month_key(date_str)` = `date_str[:7]` — the standard way to group by
  month throughout `report_data.py` and `analyze.py`.
- When adding a new CLI flag to `analyze.py`, follow the existing
  `argparse` pattern and keep the default (no-flag) behavior as the
  "full picture" report (latest month + trends + subscriptions).

## When making changes

- After editing `rules/categories.py`, run `python recategorise.py` to
  re-apply keyword rules to existing rows (manual UI overrides are kept),
  or delete `db/finance.db` and re-run `importer.py` for a full rebuild
  (overrides are lost). Mention this to the user if you edit categorisation
  rules.
- Test changes to `importer.py` parsing logic against edge cases:
  malformed amounts, unquoted commas in descriptions, missing columns,
  empty files — not just the happy path.
- Keep functions stdlib-testable without needing real bank data — use
  synthetic CSVs with fake merchant names/amounts when verifying fixes
  (see CURSOR_PROMPT.md history for examples of this pattern).
